body:
This is somewhat contrived, not a distillation of real code.

Instances `b0`, and `b1` are distinct instances of module `B`. There should not be a circular loop between `b0.a.x` and `b1.a.x`. The following code

```SystemVerilog
interface A;
  logic x;
endinterface

module B;
  A a();
endmodule

module C(A a0, A a1);
  assign a1.x = a0.x;
endmodule

module test;
  B b0();
  B b1();
  C c(b0.a, b1.a);
endmodule
```

results in the following error.

```
%Error: bug.sv:10:15: Wire inputs its own output, creating circular logic (wire x=x)
   10 |   assign a1.x = a0.x;
      |               ^
%Warning-UNOPTFLAT: bug.sv:2:9: Signal unoptimizable: Circular combinational logic: 'test.b1.a.x'
                              : ... note: In instance 'test.b1.a'
    2 |   logic x;
      |         ^
                    ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/UNOPTFLAT?v=5.030
                    ... Use "/* verilator lint_off UNOPTFLAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
                    bug.sv:2:9:      Example path: test.b1.a.x
                    bug.sv:10:15:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    bug.sv:2:9:      Example path: test.b1.a.x
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s), 1 warning(s)
```

Note that there is no error if `b0` and `b1` are instances of distinct but completely identical modules.

```
interface A;
  logic x;
endinterface

module B0;
  A a();
endmodule

module B1;
  A a();
endmodule

module C(A a0, A a1);
  assign a1.x = a0.x;
endmodule

module test;
  B0 b0();
  B1 b1();
  C c(b0.a, b1.a);
endmodule
```

> What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

`verilator --timing --trace --top-module test--binary bug.sv`

> What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?

Verilator 5.030.

> What OS and distribution are you using?

Ubuntu 22.04 under WSL.

> May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

If this look like someone who is a Verilator beginner could reasonably handle.
